1. Examples of ARIMA fitting



ARIMA(p,d,q) model

Your observation \(Y_t\) is modeled as ARIMA(p,d,q) if:

  • Take difference \(d\) times. Call it \(X_t\). \[ \bigtriangledown^d Y_t \hspace{3mm} = \hspace{3mm} X_t \]

  • Then model \(X_t\) with ARMA(p,q) model: \[ \Phi(B) \, X_t \hspace{3mm} = \hspace{3mm} \Theta(B) \, e_t \] where \(e_t\sim WN(0,\sigma^2)\).

ARIMA(p,d,q) model means you difference the data \(d\) times, then you get ARMA(\(p,q\)).



Example: Sheep Data

Annual sheep population (1000s) in England and Wales 1867 – 1939

  library(forecast)
  source('https://nmimoto.github.io/R/TS-00.txt')

  D  <- read.csv("https://nmimoto.github.io/datasets/sheep.csv", header=T)
  Sheep <- ts(D[,2], start=c(1867), freq=1)

  plot(Sheep, type="o")

  Stationarity.tests(Sheep)
## Warning in kpss.test(A): p-value smaller than printed p-value
##        KPSS   ADF    PP
## p-val: 0.01 0.554 0.211
  #--- ARIMA fit ---
  Fit1 <- auto.arima(Sheep, stepwise=FALSE, approximation=FALSE)
  Fit1

  • \(Y_t\) is ARIMA(3,1,0) without drift \[ \bigtriangledown Y_t \hspace{3mm} = \hspace{3mm} \delta + X_t \\ \]

  • \(X_t\) is ARMA(3,0) \[ X_t - \phi_1 X_{t-1} - \phi_2 X_{t-2} - \phi_3 X_{x-3} = e_t \]

  • This could mean two things \[ Y_t \hspace{3mm} = \hspace{3mm} a + b t + S_t \\ \\ Y_t \hspace{3mm} = \hspace{3mm} M_t + S_t \] \(S_t\) is stationary series. \(M_t\) is Random Walk with drift \(\delta\).

Sheep: Lenear Trend or Random Trend

  • ARIMA(3,1,0) was adequate model for Sheep data.

  • This could mean two things:

    • Sheep had linear trend going down, which dissapeared when d=1 difference was taken

    • Sheep had random trend, which dissapeared when d=1 difference was taken. (When KPSS test was applied to Sheep, it could not reject the null of the presence of the random trend.)

  • Can we pick one scenario over the other?

  Reg1 =  lm(Sheep ~ time(Sheep))
  summary(Reg1)

  • After taking the linear trend out, it is quetionable that residuals are stationary.

  • Sheep should be modeled by random trend instead of linear trend.



2. ARIMA(p,d,q) Model Selection



Model Selection in ARIMA(\(p,d,q\))

  • Use stationarity test to decide how many times to defference (\(d\)).

  • When AR(1) parameter is estimated, see if \(\phi_1\) is significantly different from 1.

  • Watch for sign of overdifferencing.



auto.arima() algorighm

Hyndman-Khandakar algorithm for automatic ARIMA modelling in

  • The number of differences \(d\) is determined using repeated KPSS tests.

  • The values of \(p\) and \(q\) are then chosen by minimizing the AICc after differencing the data \(d\) times. Rather than considering every possible combination of \(p\) and \(q\), the algorithm uses a stepwise search to traverse the model space.

    • The best model (with smallest AICc) is selected from the following four:

      ARIMA(2,d,2), ARIMA(0,d,0), ARIMA(1,d,0), ARIMA(0,d,1).

      If \(d=0\) then the constant \(c\) is included; if \(d \> 1\) then the constant \(c\) is set to zero. This is called the “current model”.

    • Variations on the current model are considered:

      vary \(p\) and/or \(q\) from the current model by \(\pm 1\); include/exclude \(c\) from the current model. The best model considered so far (either the current model, or one of these variations) becomes the new current model.

    • Repeat Step above until no lower AICc can be found.



After auto.arima()

  • Check parameter significance. If parameters are not significant, then remove from the model.

  • For value of \(d\) selected by auto.arima(), take the difference by hand, and use Stationarity.tests() to see what other tests say.

  • You can change stationarity test used by auto.arima(). Default is KPSS test.
    Type ?auto.arima to see syntax of how to change default.



Overdifferencing

  • Suppose \(\delta X_t = Y_t\) \[ Y_t \hspace{3mm} = \hspace{3mm} e_t \]

  • Each step has now little more change of being positive than negative. \[ P(e_t >0) = .54 \hspace{10mm} P(e_t \leq 0) = .46. \]

  • Take \(\bigtriangledown\) again, then you get \[ \bigtriangledown Y_t = e_t - e_{t-1} \] Now we got MA(1) with \(\theta_1 = 1\). That’s not invertible.

  • Suppose \[ \bigtriangledown X_t \hspace{3mm} = \hspace{3mm} Y_t\\ \\ Y_t \hspace{3mm} = \hspace{3mm} e_t - \theta_1 e_{t-1} \] If you take \(\bigtriangledown\) again, \[ \bigtriangledown Y_t \hspace{3mm} = \hspace{3mm} (e_t - \theta_1 e_{t-1}) - (e_{t-1} - \theta_1 e_{t-2}) \\ \\ \hspace{3mm} = \hspace{3mm} (e_t - (1+\theta_1) e_{t-1} + \theta_1 e_{t-2}) . \]

  • So \(\bigtriangledown Y_t\) is MA(2) with \[ \Theta(z) \hspace{3mm} = \hspace{3mm} 1 - (1+\theta_1) z + \theta_1 z^2 \] Root is

    \[\begin{align} \frac{-b \pm \sqrt{b^2\pm 4ac}}{2a} &= \hspace{3mm} \frac{(1+\theta_1) \pm \sqrt{(1+\theta_1)^2-4\theta_1}}{ 2\theta_1} \\ \\ &= \hspace{3mm} \frac{(1+\theta_1) \pm \sqrt{1- 2 \theta_1 + \theta_1^2}}{ 2 \theta_1} \\ \\ &= \hspace{3mm} \frac{(1+\theta_1) \pm \sqrt{(1- \theta_1)^2}}{ 2 \theta_1} \\ \\ &= \hspace{3mm} \frac{2}{2 \theta_1} \hspace{3mm} \mbox{or} \hspace{3mm} \frac{2\theta_1}{2 \theta_1} \end{align}\] That’s a unit root!

  • Testing Unit-Root in MA(q) polynomials \(\to\) not fully resolved.

  • Test Unit-Root in MA(1) \(\to\) see if \(\hat\theta_1\) is significantly different from -1.



ARMA with same polynomials

  • Suppose you have ARMA(1,1) with \[ Y_t - .5 Y_{t-1} = e_t - .5 e_{t-1} \] Then this is

    \[\begin{align} (1-.5 B) Y_t &= \hspace{3mm} (1-.5 B) e_t \\\\ &= \hspace{3mm} e_t \end{align}\]

So \(Y_t\) is just a white noise.

  • larain in package TSA is good example for this.




Example: LArain data

Check for same characteristic polynomials.

  library(forecast) 
  source('https://nmimoto.github.io/R/TS-00.txt') 

  acf.orig <- acf;  library(TSA);  acf <- acf.orig

  data(larain)

  plot(larain, type="o")

  Arima(larain, order=c(1,0,1))

## 
## Coefficients:
##           ar1     ma1     mean
##       -0.3402  0.3006  14.8848

  • When orders of AR and MA mathces, watch out for equal value of parameters. It may indicate WN.

  • If MA(1) gives you \(-1\), it indicates the over-differencing.





Summary

  • ARIMA(p,d,q) model means that difference was taken d times, then ARMA(p,q) model was fit.

  • auto.arima() uses KPSS test as a guide for choosing d automatically. It is always a good idea to use Stationarity.tests and see if the choice of d is reasonable.

  • If the series was over-differenced, force-fitting MA(1) produces \(\hat \theta_1\) that is too close to -1.

  • If the series was under-differenced, force-fitting AR(1) gives \(\hat \phi_1\) that is too close to \(\pm 1\). You can also use Stationarity.tests() as a guide for under-differencing.

  • When polynomials of AR and MA are the same, it just mean that you got WN.
